Looking forward to 2021, 61 per cent believe that the new year will be a better year than the previous one, with some 27 per cent of the respondents hopeful that the economy will improve while another 15 per cent are looking forward to receiving vaccinations against Covid-19.
“The findings were that overall, 38 per cent were very optimistic, 23 per cent somewhat optimistic, 30 per cent averagely optimistic, while 6 per cent were not optimistic and another 3 per cent not at all optimistic,” said Mr Nyabundi.
Of those optimistic, 27 per cent were hopeful that the economy will improve, 15 per cent that Kenyans will receive the vaccine against Covid-19, 14 per cent that their finances will improve, 10 per cent that they will get a job, while 9 per cent were optimistic that their businesses will expand.
Some 9 per cent are of the feeling that the upcoming referendum will divide the country while another 8 per cent believe that there will be an increase in ethnic tensions and rivalry. The outlook offers hope to millions plunged into poverty by the devastating shocks of Covid-19 containment measures. Betting Control and Licensing Board (BCLB) says the firm has not been licensed to provide services advertised on its website. In his new year’s message to the country, the President called for a renewal of minds in the New Year 2021. He paraded the newly elected Msambweni MP Feisal Bader as the “firstborn” of the so called Hustler's Movement. Ever since Abiy Ahmed came to power, the Tigray regional government has been at odds with the central government.